{"title_page": "Joshua Claybourn", "text_new": "{{short description|American attorney, author, and historian|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Joshua Claybourn\n|image       = Claybourn-pp.jpg\n|imagesize   = \n|caption     = \n|birth_name  = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1981|06|10}}\n|birth_place = [[Evansville, Indiana|Evansville]], [[Indiana]], U.S.\n|occupation  = Lawyer, historian\n|boards      = [[Abraham Lincoln Association]], [[Abraham Lincoln Institute]]\n|alma_mater  = [[Kelley School of Business]] <small>([[Bachelor of science|B.S.]])</small><br />[[Indiana University Robert H. McKinney School of Law|Indiana Univ. School of Law]] <small>([[Juris Doctor|J.D.]])</small>\n|website     = {{url|joshclaybourn.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Joshua Claybourn''' is an American attorney, author, and historian.\n\n==Early life and education==\nClaybourn is a native of [[Evansville, Indiana]]. He graduated from [[North High School (Evansville)|North High School]] and earned a bachelor's degree from [[Indiana University Bloomington|Indiana University]] [[Kelley School of Business]]. Thereafter he earned a law degree from [[Indiana University Robert H. McKinney School of Law]] and served as a research assistant to Professor [[Gerard Magliocca]] during his work on ''Andrew Jackson and the Constitution: The Rise and Fall of Generational Regimes''.<ref name=\"writing\" />\n\n==Career==\n===Legal work===\nClaybourn is an attorney with the law firm of [[Jackson Kelly (law firm)|Jackson Kelly]] representing governmental entities and officials, as well as businesses and corporations.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hall|first1=Shannon|title=Chandler appoints new attorney|url=http://www.courierpress.com/news/local/warrick/chandler-appoints-new-attorney-2884cd6d-1d30-5d5a-e053-0100007fb8df-364257441.html|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=Courier & Press|date=January 5, 2016}}</ref> Citing Article 1, Section 2 of the [[United States Constitution]], Claybourn appeared before the Indiana Election Commission and successfully challenged a 23-year-old person's legal right to appear on the ballot as a candidate for Congress in [[Indiana's 8th congressional district]].<ref name=\"Bucshon 2016\">{{cite news|last1=Langhorne|first1=Thomas|title=Bucshon supporter challenges 23-year-old woman's right to run for 8th District|url=http://www.courierpress.com/news/politics/elections/national/bucshon-supporter-challenges-23-year-old-womans-right-to-run-for-8th-district-2bfe3bec-d5d4-3ee4-e05-369340551.html|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=Courier & Press|date=February 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Osowski|first1=Zach|title=Tied commission vote will keep Young on U.S. Senate ballot|url=http://www.courierpress.com/news/politics/national/tied-commission-vote-will-keep-young-on-us-senate-ballot--for-now-2c20b7a4-9d09-2dbd-e053-0100007fa2-369476442.html|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=Courier & Press|date=February 19, 2016}}</ref> He previously served as an adjunct professor of business law at the [[University of Evansville]]. Despite high-profile criticism of [[Donald Trump]], members of his [[Presidential transition of Donald Trump|transition team]] sought Claybourn's interest in a legal role with the administration, suggesting his involvement would be \"good for unity\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Berg|first1=Rebecca|title=Pence Role as Transition Leader Hints at Insider Mix|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2016/11/12/pence_role_as_transition_leader_hints_at_insider_mix_132332.html|publisher=RealClear Politics|date=November 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Historian and pundit===\nMuch of Claybourn's scholarship focuses on [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s youth in Indiana. He is a co-editor (with [[William Bartelt]]) of ''Abe\u2019s Youth: Shaping the Future President'' ([[Indiana University Press]], 2019).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Claybourn |first1=Joshua |title=From the Desk of Joshua A. Claybourn: Finding Our Sense of National Identity |url=https://unpblog.com/2018/09/07/from-the-desk-of-joshua-a-claybourn-finding-our-sense-of-national-identity/ |website=UNP Blog |publisher=University of Nebraska Press |accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Writing & Research|url=http://www.joshclaybourn.com/writing/|website=Joshua Claybourn|accessdate=November 21, 2017}}</ref> He is a board member of both the [[Abraham Lincoln Association]] and [[Abraham Lincoln Institute]], former chair of the Southern Indiana Civil War Roundtable,<ref>{{cite web |title=About |url=http://www.sicwrt.org/about/ |website=Southern Indiana Civil War Roundtable |accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref> and former trustee and president of the [[Evansville Vanderburgh Public Library]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://evpl.org/aboutus/board/|title=Board of Trustees|year=2009|publisher=Evansville Vanderburgh Public Library|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202205723/http://evpl.org/aboutus/board/|archivedate=February 2, 2009|accessdate=January 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://evpl.org/aboutus/board/|title=Board of Trustees|year=2013|publisher=Evansville Vanderburgh Public Library|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130111084118/http://evpl.org/aboutus/board/|archivedate=January 11, 2013|accessdate=January 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nClaybourn is also editor of ''Our American Story: The Search for a Shared National Narrative'' ([[University of Nebraska Press#Potomac Books|Potomac Books]], 2019), a collection of essays by theorists, historians, and politicians addressing the possibility of a shared narrative within a country divided by political polarization. Contributors to the project include [[Cass Sunstein]], [[Gordon S. Wood]], [[John Danforth]], [[Richard Epstein]], [[David Blight]], [[Markos Moulitsas]], [[Alan Taylor (historian)|Alan Taylor]], [[Eleanor Clift]], [[Jim Banks]], [[Nikolas Gvosdev]], [[Ilya Somin]], Cherie Harder, [[Gerard Magliocca]], [[Jason Kuznicki]], Cody Delistraty, Spencer Boyer, Ali Wyne, and [[James Wertsch]]. ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' wrote that the book's \"responses are all over the map, provocatively so . . .\"<ref>{{cite news |title=KIRKUS REVIEW |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/joshua-claybourn/our-american-story/ |accessdate=8 April 2019 |agency=Kirkus Reviews |date=24 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nClaybourn is an adjunct scholar with the [[Indiana Policy Review Foundation]] and his work has appeared in ''[[USA Today]]'', ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'', ''[[The Federalist (website)|The Federalist]]'', ''[[The American Spectator]]'', National Review Online, ''[[American Thinker]]'', and ''[[World (magazine)|World Magazine]]'', as well as regional publications such as the ''[[Indianapolis Star]]'', ''[[Evansville Courier & Press]]'', ''[[The News-Sentinel]]'', and ''[[The Herald-Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joshua Claybourn|url=http://thefederalist.com/author/joshuaclaybourn/|website=The Federalist|accessdate=July 27, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"writing\">{{cite web|title=Writing & Research|url=http://www.joshclaybourn.com/writing/|website=Joshua Claybourn}}</ref> On television he has commented on current events on [[CNN]], [[MSNBC]], and [[NHK]]. Previously he was a blogger that radio talk show host [[Hugh Hewitt]] included among the \"next generation of bloggers\" and a reason \"to be very optimistic about the future of the [[blogosphere]].\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hewitt|first1=Hugh|title=The Next Generation of Bloggers|url=http://www.hughhewitt.com/the-next-generation-of-bloggers/|accessdate=July 27, 2016}}</ref> Claybourn is an outspoken advocate of [[Home rule in the United States|home rule]], a principle in Indiana and several other states that generally grants municipalities the power to govern themselves as they see fit.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Claybourn|first1=Joshua|title=Claybourn: In defense of Hoosier home rule|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/opinion/2017/05/07/claybourn-defense-hoosier-home-rule/101289696/|accessdate=May 7, 2017|publisher=Indianapolis Star|date=May 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Claybourn|first1=Joshua|title=General Assembly home rule encroachments|url=http://www.howeypolitics.com/Content/Default/Lead-Story/Article/Joshua-Claybourn-General-Assembly-home-rule-encroachments/-3/346/15251|accessdate=May 7, 2017|publisher=Howey Politics Indiana|date=May 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nClaybourn was cited as a \"key supporter\" of Congressman [[Larry Bucshon]] of {{ushr|IN|8}}.<ref name=\"Bucshon 2016\" /> He was a principal adviser to Evansville Mayor [[Lloyd Winnecke]]'s campaign and was a part of Winnecke's 2012 transition team.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sarkissian|first1=Arek|title=Winnecke: Transition team has received 220 resumes for 37 positions|url=http://www.courierpress.com/news/local/326685301.html|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=Courier & Press|date=December 2, 2011}}</ref> He also served as a top adviser during Winnecke's successful 2015 re-election campaign, which made Winnecke the first Republican Evansville mayor to be re-elected in 40 years.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Martin|first1=John|title=Winnecke elected to second term as Evansville mayor|url=http://www.courierpress.com/news/politics/elections/local/winnecke-elected-to-second-term-as-evansville-mayor-23a6ecf0-824d-667c-e053-0100007f1590-340018201.html|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=Courier & Press|date=November 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Claybourn was selected as an Indiana delegate to the [[2016 Republican National Convention]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cook|first1=Tony|title=Indiana GOP names delegates to Republican National Convention|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/news/politics/2016/04/14/indiana-gop-names-delegates-republican-national-convention/83039428/|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=Indianapolis Star|date=April 14, 2016}}</ref> A day after [[Donald Trump]]'s win in the Indiana primary which made Trump the party's presumptive nominee, Claybourn was one of the first to resign his position as a delegate because he \"could not in good conscience attend a coronation and celebration of Donald Trump\".<ref name=\"Trump 2016\">{{cite news|last1=Peters|first1=Jeremy|title='I Can Watch It on TV': Excuses for Republicans Skipping a Donald Trump Convention|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/02/us/politics/donald-trump-republican-convention.html|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=New York Times|date=June 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kopan|first1=Tal|title=With Trump as nominee, delegate spots lose appeal for Republicans|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/05/11/politics/republican-delegates-back-out-donald-trump/?iid=ob_lockedrail_topeditorial|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=CNN|date=May 12, 2016}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' noted Mr. Claybourn would have been bound to vote for Mr. Trump on the first ballot, \"a step he said he simply could not stomach\".<ref name=\"Trump 2016\" /> In a statement Claybourn said, \"Donald J. Trump is the Republican Party's nominee. But he will not be my nominee, and I will not attend a convention celebrating his candidacy.\"<ref name=\"Trump 2016\" />\n\n==Publications==\n* Claybourn, Joshua A., ed. ''Our American Story: The Search for a Shared National Narrative''. Lincoln: Potomac Books, 2019.\n* Bartelt, William, and Joshua A. Claybourn, eds. ''Abe\u2019s Youth: Shaping the Future President''. Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 2019.\n* Claybourn, Joshua A., ed. ''Born of Clay: The Story of the Claiborne \u00b7 Claybourn \u00b7 Clayborn Families in the United States''. Evansville: Claybourn Genealogical Society, 2016.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://ballotpedia.org/Josh_Claybourn Profile] - [[Ballotpedia]]\n* [http://www.joshclaybourn.com/ Personal home page]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Claybourn, Joshua}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:Indiana Republicans]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Evansville, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Leadership Institute alumni and associates]]\n[[Category:Stop Trump movement]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Historians of Abraham Lincoln]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American attorney, author, and historian|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Joshua Claybourn\n|image       = Claybourn-pp.jpg\n|imagesize   = \n|caption     = \n|birth_name  = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1981|06|10}}\n|birth_place = [[Evansville, Indiana|Evansville]], [[Indiana]], U.S.\n|occupation  = Lawyer, historian\n|boards      = [[Abraham Lincoln Association]], [[Abraham Lincoln Institute]]\n|alma_mater  = [[Kelley School of Business]] <small>([[Bachelor of science|B.S.]])</small><br />[[Indiana University Robert H. McKinney School of Law|Indiana Univ. School of Law]] <small>([[Juris Doctor|J.D.]])</small>\n|website     = {{url|joshclaybourn.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Joshua Claybourn''' is an American attorney, author, and historian.\n\n==Early life and education==\nClaybourn is a native of [[Evansville, Indiana]]. He graduated from [[North High School (Evansville)|North High School]] and earned a bachelor's degree from [[Indiana University Bloomington|Indiana University]] [[Kelley School of Business]]. Thereafter he earned a law degree from [[Indiana University Robert H. McKinney School of Law]] and served as a research assistant to Professor [[Gerard Magliocca]] during his work on ''Andrew Jackson and the Constitution: The Rise and Fall of Generational Regimes''.<ref name=\"writing\" />\n\n==Career==\n===Legal work===\nClaybourn is an attorney with the law firm of [[Jackson Kelly (law firm)|Jackson Kelly]] representing governmental entities and officials, as well as businesses and corporations.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hall|first1=Shannon|title=Chandler appoints new attorney|url=http://www.courierpress.com/news/local/warrick/chandler-appoints-new-attorney-2884cd6d-1d30-5d5a-e053-0100007fb8df-364257441.html|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=Courier & Press|date=January 5, 2016}}</ref> Citing Article 1, Section 2 of the [[United States Constitution]], Claybourn appeared before the Indiana Election Commission and successfully challenged a 23-year-old person's legal right to appear on the ballot as a candidate for Congress in [[Indiana's 8th congressional district]].<ref name=\"Bucshon 2016\">{{cite news|last1=Langhorne|first1=Thomas|title=Bucshon supporter challenges 23-year-old woman's right to run for 8th District|url=http://www.courierpress.com/news/politics/elections/national/bucshon-supporter-challenges-23-year-old-womans-right-to-run-for-8th-district-2bfe3bec-d5d4-3ee4-e05-369340551.html|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=Courier & Press|date=February 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Osowski|first1=Zach|title=Tied commission vote will keep Young on U.S. Senate ballot|url=http://www.courierpress.com/news/politics/national/tied-commission-vote-will-keep-young-on-us-senate-ballot--for-now-2c20b7a4-9d09-2dbd-e053-0100007fa2-369476442.html|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=Courier & Press|date=February 19, 2016}}</ref> He previously served as an adjunct professor of business law at the [[University of Evansville]]. Despite high-profile criticism of [[Donald Trump]], members of his [[Presidential transition of Donald Trump|transition team]] sought Claybourn's interest in a legal role with the administration, suggesting his involvement would be \"good for unity\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Berg|first1=Rebecca|title=Pence Role as Transition Leader Hints at Insider Mix|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2016/11/12/pence_role_as_transition_leader_hints_at_insider_mix_132332.html|publisher=RealClear Politics|date=November 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Historian and pundit===\nMuch of Claybourn's scholarship focuses on [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s youth in Indiana. He is a co-editor (with [[William Bartelt]]) of ''Abe\u2019s Youth: Shaping the Future President'' ([[Indiana University Press]], 2019).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Claybourn |first1=Joshua |title=From the Desk of Joshua A. Claybourn: Finding Our Sense of National Identity |url=https://unpblog.com/2018/09/07/from-the-desk-of-joshua-a-claybourn-finding-our-sense-of-national-identity/ |website=UNP Blog |publisher=University of Nebraska Press |accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Writing & Research|url=http://www.joshclaybourn.com/writing/|website=Joshua Claybourn|accessdate=November 21, 2017}}</ref> He is a board member of both the [[Abraham Lincoln Association]] and [[Abraham Lincoln Institute]], former chair of the Southern Indiana Civil War Roundtable,<ref>{{cite web |title=About |url=http://www.sicwrt.org/about/ |website=Southern Indiana Civil War Roundtable |accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref> and former trustee and president of the [[Evansville Vanderburgh Public Library]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://evpl.org/aboutus/board/|title=Board of Trustees|year=2009|publisher=Evansville Vanderburgh Public Library|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202205723/http://evpl.org/aboutus/board/|archivedate=February 2, 2009|accessdate=January 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://evpl.org/aboutus/board/|title=Board of Trustees|year=2013|publisher=Evansville Vanderburgh Public Library|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130111084118/http://evpl.org/aboutus/board/|archivedate=January 11, 2013|accessdate=January 22, 2018}}</ref> \n\nClaybourn is also editor of ''Our American Story: The Search for a Shared National Narrative'' ([[University of Nebraska Press#Potomac Books|Potomac Books]], 2019), a collection of essays by theorists, historians, and politicians addressing the possibility of a shared narrative within a country divided by political polarization. Contributors to the project include [[Cass Sunstein]], [[Gordon S. Wood]], [[John Danforth]], [[Richard Epstein]], [[David Blight]], [[Markos Moulitsas]], [[Alan Taylor (historian)|Alan Taylor]], [[Eleanor Clift]], [[Jim Banks]], [[Nikolas Gvosdev]], [[Ilya Somin]], Cherie Harder, [[Gerard Magliocca]], [[Jason Kuznicki]], Cody Delistraty, Spencer Boyer, Ali Wyne, and [[James Wertsch]]. ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' wrote that the book's \"responses are all over the map, provocatively so . . .\"<ref>{{cite news |title=KIRKUS REVIEW |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/joshua-claybourn/our-american-story/ |accessdate=8 April 2019 |agency=Kirkus Reviews |date=24 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nClaybourn is an adjunct scholar with the [[Indiana Policy Review Foundation]] and his work has appeared in ''[[USA Today]]'', ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'', ''[[The Federalist (website)|The Federalist]]'', ''[[The American Spectator]]'', National Review Online, ''[[American Thinker]]'', and ''[[World (magazine)|World Magazine]]'', as well as regional publications such as the ''[[Indianapolis Star]]'', ''[[Evansville Courier & Press]]'', ''[[The News-Sentinel]]'', and ''[[The Herald-Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joshua Claybourn|url=http://thefederalist.com/author/joshuaclaybourn/|website=The Federalist|accessdate=July 27, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"writing\">{{cite web|title=Writing & Research|url=http://www.joshclaybourn.com/writing/|website=Joshua Claybourn}}</ref> On television he has commented on current events on [[CNN]], [[MSNBC]], and [[NHK]]. Previously he was a blogger that radio talk show host [[Hugh Hewitt]] included among the \"next generation of bloggers\" and a reason \"to be very optimistic about the future of the [[blogosphere]].\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hewitt|first1=Hugh|title=The Next Generation of Bloggers|url=http://www.hughhewitt.com/the-next-generation-of-bloggers/|accessdate=July 27, 2016}}</ref> Claybourn is an outspoken advocate of [[Home rule in the United States|home rule]], a principle in Indiana and several other states that generally grants municipalities the power to govern themselves as they see fit.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Claybourn|first1=Joshua|title=Claybourn: In defense of Hoosier home rule|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/opinion/2017/05/07/claybourn-defense-hoosier-home-rule/101289696/|accessdate=May 7, 2017|publisher=Indianapolis Star|date=May 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Claybourn|first1=Joshua|title=General Assembly home rule encroachments|url=http://www.howeypolitics.com/Content/Default/Lead-Story/Article/Joshua-Claybourn-General-Assembly-home-rule-encroachments/-3/346/15251|accessdate=May 7, 2017|publisher=Howey Politics Indiana|date=May 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nClaybourn was cited as a \"key supporter\" of Congressman [[Larry Bucshon]] of {{ushr|IN|8}}.<ref name=\"Bucshon 2016\" /> He was a principal adviser to Evansville Mayor [[Lloyd Winnecke]]'s campaign and was a part of Winnecke's 2012 transition team.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sarkissian|first1=Arek|title=Winnecke: Transition team has received 220 resumes for 37 positions|url=http://www.courierpress.com/news/local/326685301.html|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=Courier & Press|date=December 2, 2011}}</ref> He also served as a top adviser during Winnecke's successful 2015 re-election campaign, which made Winnecke the first Republican Evansville mayor to be re-elected in 40 years.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Martin|first1=John|title=Winnecke elected to second term as Evansville mayor|url=http://www.courierpress.com/news/politics/elections/local/winnecke-elected-to-second-term-as-evansville-mayor-23a6ecf0-824d-667c-e053-0100007f1590-340018201.html|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=Courier & Press|date=November 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Claybourn was selected as an Indiana delegate to the [[2016 Republican National Convention]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cook|first1=Tony|title=Indiana GOP names delegates to Republican National Convention|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/news/politics/2016/04/14/indiana-gop-names-delegates-republican-national-convention/83039428/|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=Indianapolis Star|date=April 14, 2016}}</ref> A day after [[Donald Trump]]'s win in the Indiana primary which made Trump the party's presumptive nominee, Claybourn was one of the first to resign his position as a delegate because he \"could not in good conscience attend a coronation and celebration of Donald Trump\".<ref name=\"Trump 2016\">{{cite news|last1=Peters|first1=Jeremy|title='I Can Watch It on TV': Excuses for Republicans Skipping a Donald Trump Convention|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/02/us/politics/donald-trump-republican-convention.html|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=New York Times|date=June 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kopan|first1=Tal|title=With Trump as nominee, delegate spots lose appeal for Republicans|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/05/11/politics/republican-delegates-back-out-donald-trump/?iid=ob_lockedrail_topeditorial|accessdate=July 27, 2016|publisher=CNN|date=May 12, 2016}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' noted Mr. Claybourn would have been bound to vote for Mr. Trump on the first ballot, \"a step he said he simply could not stomach\".<ref name=\"Trump 2016\" /> In a statement Claybourn said, \"Donald J. Trump is the Republican Party's nominee. But he will not be my nominee, and I will not attend a convention celebrating his candidacy.\"<ref name=\"Trump 2016\" />\n\n==Publications==\n* Claybourn, Joshua A., ed. ''Our American Story: The Search for a Shared National Narrative''. Lincoln: Potomac Books, 2019.\n* Bartelt, William, and Joshua A. Claybourn, eds. ''Abe\u2019s Youth: Shaping the Future President''. Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 2019.\n* Claybourn, Joshua A., ed. ''Born of Clay: The Story of the Claiborne \u00b7 Claybourn \u00b7 Clayborn Families in the United States''. Evansville: Claybourn Genealogical Society, 2016.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://ballotpedia.org/Josh_Claybourn Profile] - [[Ballotpedia]]\n* [http://www.joshclaybourn.com/ Personal home page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Claybourn, Joshua}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:Indiana Republicans]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Evansville, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Leadership Institute alumni and associates]]\n[[Category:Stop Trump movement]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Historians of Abraham Lincoln]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joshua_Claybourn"}
