{"title_page": "Joshua Brown (writer)", "text_new": "'''Joshua Morgan Brown''' is an [[United States|American]] [[author]], [[columnist]], [[blogger]], [[Pundit|commentator]] on [[CNBC]], and [[CEO]] of [[New York City]]-based Ritholtz Wealth Management, an independent investment advisory firm he founded with [[Barry Ritholtz]]. He is also a contributing columnist to [[Yahoo! Finance]], ''[[Business Insider]]'', and serves on the Board of Advisors for Brightscope<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.riabiz.com/a/12053576/reformed-broker-and-blogger-downtown-josh-brown-joins-brightscopes-advisory-board | title='Reformed Broker' and blogger 'Downtown' Josh Brown joins BrightScope's advisory board | publisher=Riabiz.com | date=March 14, 2012 | accessdate=July 5, 2016 | author=Shidler, Lisa}}</ref>  and Upside.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/upside-powers-ritholtz-wealth-managements-new-digital-offering-called-liftoff-2014-10-01 | title=Upside Powers Ritholtz Wealth Management's New Digital Offering, Called Liftoff | publisher=[[MarketWatch]].com | date=October 1, 2014 | accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref> \"Downtown\" Josh Brown was ranked the No. 1 financial [[Twitter]] follow by ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' in 2013.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324662404578334890346873944/ |title=The Best Tweets for Your Money |publisher=Wall Street Journal |date=March 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Writing==\nBrown is the author of ''Backstage Wallstreet'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/moneybuilder/2012/12/27/review-backstage-wall-street/ |title=Review: Backstage Wall Street |newspaper=[[Forbes]] |date=December 27, 2012 |first=Charles |last=Sizemore}}</ref> published in 2012. His second book was released in 2014, ''Clash Of The Financial Pundits'' co-authored with [[CNBC]] and [[Yahoo! Finance]] commentator Jeff Macke. He is also the author of ''The Reformed Broker'', a widely read blog about \"markets, politics, economics, media, culture and finance\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.marketwatch.com/thetell/2014/06/11/you-should-be-reading-these-five-financial-bloggers/ |title=Here are five finance bloggers you should be reading |publisher=Marketwatch |date=June 11, 2014}}</ref> The Reformed Broker blog celebrated its fifth anniversary on November 10, 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://thereformedbroker.com/2013/11/10/i-am-the-one-who-blogs-trb-turns-five/ | title=I Am The One Who Blogs: TRB Turns Five | publisher=Thereformedbroker.com | date=November 10, 2013 | accessdate=July 5, 2016 | author=Brown, Joshua M.}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBrown was educated at the [[University of Maryland]], attaining his Series 7 license{{explanation needed|This is meaningless without saying what it is.|date=January 2020}} in 1997 while still in school.\n\n==Personal life==\nBrown is a resident of [[Long Island, New York]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thereformedbroker.com The Reformed Broker (Brown's blog)]\n* [https://www.cnbc.com/id/101098975# CNBC Contributor Page]\n* [https://www.google.com/webhp?tab=ww&ei=9k8uVI22KIGyyAT934H4Ag&ved=0CAcQ1S4&gws_rd=ssl#q=josh%20brown%20yahoo%20finance Yahoo Finance Contributions]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Joshua}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American business writers]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American economics writers]]\n[[Category:American finance and investment writers]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "'''Joshua Morgan Brown''' is an [[United States|American]] [[author]], [[columnist]], [[blogger]], [[Pundit|commentator]] on [[CNBC]], and [[CEO]] of [[New York City]]-based Ritholtz Wealth Management, an independent investment advisory firm he founded with [[Barry Ritholtz]]. He is also a contributing columnist to [[Yahoo! Finance]], ''[[Business Insider]]'', and serves on the Board of Advisors for Brightscope<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.riabiz.com/a/12053576/reformed-broker-and-blogger-downtown-josh-brown-joins-brightscopes-advisory-board | title='Reformed Broker' and blogger 'Downtown' Josh Brown joins BrightScope's advisory board | publisher=Riabiz.com | date=March 14, 2012 | accessdate=July 5, 2016 | author=Shidler, Lisa}}</ref>  and Upside.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/upside-powers-ritholtz-wealth-managements-new-digital-offering-called-liftoff-2014-10-01 | title=Upside Powers Ritholtz Wealth Management's New Digital Offering, Called Liftoff | publisher=[[MarketWatch]].com | date=October 1, 2014 | accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref> \"Downtown\" Josh Brown was ranked the No. 1 financial [[Twitter]] follow by ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' in 2013.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324662404578334890346873944/ |title=The Best Tweets for Your Money |publisher=Wall Street Journal |date=March 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Writing==\nBrown is the author of ''Backstage Wallstreet'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/moneybuilder/2012/12/27/review-backstage-wall-street/ |title=Review: Backstage Wall Street |newspaper=[[Forbes]] |date=December 27, 2012 |first=Charles |last=Sizemore}}</ref> published in 2012. His second book was released in 2014, ''Clash Of The Financial Pundits'' co-authored with [[CNBC]] and [[Yahoo! Finance]] commentator Jeff Macke. He is also the author of ''The Reformed Broker'', a widely read blog about \"markets, politics, economics, media, culture and finance\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.marketwatch.com/thetell/2014/06/11/you-should-be-reading-these-five-financial-bloggers/ |title=Here are five finance bloggers you should be reading |publisher=Marketwatch |date=June 11, 2014}}</ref> The Reformed Broker blog celebrated its fifth anniversary on November 10, 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://thereformedbroker.com/2013/11/10/i-am-the-one-who-blogs-trb-turns-five/ | title=I Am The One Who Blogs: TRB Turns Five | publisher=Thereformedbroker.com | date=November 10, 2013 | accessdate=July 5, 2016 | author=Brown, Joshua M.}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBrown was educated at the [[University of Maryland]], attaining his Series 7 license{{explanation needed|This is meaningless without saying what it is.|date=January 2020}} in 1997 while still in school.\n\n==Personal life==\nBrown is a resident of [[Long Island, New York]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thereformedbroker.com The Reformed Broker (Brown's blog)]\n* [https://www.cnbc.com/id/101098975# CNBC Contributor Page]\n* [https://www.google.com/webhp?tab=ww&ei=9k8uVI22KIGyyAT934H4Ag&ved=0CAcQ1S4&gws_rd=ssl#q=josh%20brown%20yahoo%20finance Yahoo Finance Contributions]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Joshua}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American business writers]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American economics writers]]\n[[Category:American finance and investment writers]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joshua_Brown_(writer)"}
{"title_page": "Canadian federal election results in Eastern Montreal", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Canadian federal election results\n| year1 = 2019\n| party1c = Liberal\n| seats1c = 3\n| party1b = BQ\n| seats1b = 1\n| party1a = NDP\n| seats1a = 1\n| year2 = 2015\n| party2a = NDP\n| seats2a = 3\n| party2b = BQ\n| seats2b = 1\n| party2c = Liberal\n| seats2c = 1\n| year3 = 2011\n| party3a = NDP\n| seats3a = 5\n| year4 = 2008\n| party4a = BQ\n| seats4a = 4\n| party4b = Liberal\n| seats4b = 1\n| year5 = 2006\n| party5a = BQ\n| seats5a = 4\n| party5b = Liberal\n| seats5b = 1\n| year6 = 2004\n| party6a = BQ\n| seats6a = 4\n| party6b = Liberal\n| seats6b = 1\n| year7 = 2000\n| party7a = BQ\n| seats7a = 4\n| party7b = Liberal\n| seats7b = 1\n| year8 = 1997\n| party8a = BQ\n| seats8a = 4\n| party8b = Liberal\n| seats8b = 1\n| year9 = 1993\n| party9a = BQ\n| seats9a = 5\n| year10 = [[1988 Canadian federal election|1988]]\n| party10a = Liberal\n| seats10a = 1\n| party10b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats10b = 4\n| year11 = [[1984 Canadian federal election|1984]]\n| party11a = Liberal\n| seats11a = 2\n| party11b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats11b = 4\n| year12 = [[1980 Canadian federal election|1980]]\n| party12a = Liberal\n| seats12a = 6\n| year13 = [[1979 Canadian federal election|1979]]\n| party13a = Liberal\n| seats13a = 6\n| year14 = [[1974 Canadian federal election|1974]]\n| party14a = Liberal\n| seats14a = 7\n| year15 = [[1972 Canadian federal election|1972]]\n| party15a = Liberal\n| seats15a = 7\n| year16 = [[1968 Canadian federal election|1968]]\n| party16a = Liberal\n| seats16a = 6\n| party16b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats16b = 1\n| year17 = [[1965 Canadian federal election|1965]]\n| party17a = Liberal\n| seats17a = 6\n| party17b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats17b = 1\n| year18 = [[1963 Canadian federal election|1963]]\n| party18a = Liberal\n| seats18a = 6\n| party18b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats18b = 1\n| year19 = [[1962 Canadian federal election|1962]]\n| party19a = Liberal\n| seats19a = 6\n| party19b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats19b = 1\n| year20 = [[1958 Canadian federal election|1958]]\n| party20a = Liberal\n| seats20a = 4\n| party20b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats20b = 3\n| year21 = [[1957 Canadian federal election|1957]]\n| party21a = Liberal\n| seats21a = 7\n| year22 = [[1953 Canadian federal election|1953]]\n| party22a = Liberal\n| seats22a = 7\n| year23 = [[1949 Canadian federal election|1949]]\n| party23a = Liberal\n| seats23a = 7\n| year24 = [[1945 Canadian federal election|1945]]\n| party24a = Liberal\n| seats24a = 6\n| year25 = [[1940 Canadian federal election|1940]]\n| party25a = Liberal\n| seats25a = 6\n| year26 = [[1935 Canadian federal election|1935]]\n| party26a = Liberal\n| seats26a = 6\n| year27 = [[1930 Canadian federal election|1930]]\n| party27a = Liberal\n| seats27a = 4\n| year28 = [[1926 Canadian federal election|1926]]\n| party28a = Liberal\n| seats28a = 4\n| year29 = [[1925 Canadian federal election|1925]]\n| party29a = Liberal\n| seats29a = 4\n}}\n'''Canadian federal elections''' have provided the following '''results''' in '''Eastern Montreal'''.\n\n==Regional Profile==\nThe eastern end of the [[Island of Montreal]] was the birthplace of the sovereigntist movement, and remained a sovereigntist stronghold for four decades. During this time, whenever the [[Parti Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]] won provincially, the entire eastern half of the island was coated light blue. Federally, it was the [[Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]]'s power base from 1993 to 2011, partly due to its [[left-wing politics|leftist]] bent. With the exception of ethnic areas that protrude from Northern Montreal into the East Island's Honor\u00e9-Mercier riding, where [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] support is strong, the area is relatively homogeneously Francophone and lower-income, a recipe for Bloc dominance. Prior to the rise of the Bloc, the region voted solidly Liberal for decades before being swept up in the [[Brian Mulroney]] tide, electing Quebec nationalists under the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]] banner.  The [[Conservative Party of Canada]] has never approached this level of support, and eastern Montreal is currently the weakest region in Canada for the Tories. In 2011, the federalist [[New Democratic Party of Canada|NDP]] swept every seat in this region amid the surge of popular support in the province and the concurrent Bloc meltdown, in all but one case by well over 6,000 votes.  The NDP surge even cost longtime Bloc leader [[Gilles Duceppe]] his seat in [[Laurier-Sainte-Marie]].\n\nThe NDP largely held its gains in 2015, losing Honor\u00e9-Mercier to the Liberals and [[La Pointe-de-l'\u00cele]]\u2014long reckoned as the most strongly sovereigntist riding in Quebec\u2014to the Bloc.  However, Duceppe came up well short in his bid to retake his old riding. In 2019, however, the NDP was cut down to just one riding in eastern Montreal, with the Bloc holding onto La Pointe-de-l'\u00cele and the Liberals taking the other three.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"10\"|2004 ELECTION RESULTS CITY OF MONTREAL\n|-\n!align=\"centre\" colspan=2 rowspan=2|Party\n!align=\"centre\" colspan=2|[[Canadian federal election results in Western Montreal|Western]]\n!align=\"centre\" colspan=2|Eastern\n!align=\"centre\" colspan=2|[[Canadian federal election results in Northern Montreal and Laval|Northern]]\n!align=\"centre\" colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!align=\"right\"| Votes\n!align=\"right\"|%\n!align=\"right\"| Votes\n!align=\"right\"|%\n!align=\"right\"| Votes\n!align=\"right\"|%\n!align=\"right\"| Votes\n!align=\"right\"|%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row}} \n| style=\"width: 130px\" |[[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n|align=\"right\"|224,636\n|align=\"right\"|57.5\n|align=\"right\"|64,554\n|align=\"right\"|27.1\n|align=\"right\"|84,937\n|align=\"right\"|49.4\