xception of ethnic areas that protrude from Northern Montreal into the East Island's Honor\u00e9-Mercier riding, where [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] support is strong, the area is relatively homogeneously Francophone and lower-income, a recipe for Bloc dominance. Prior to the rise of the Bloc, the region voted solidly Liberal for decades before being swept up in the [[Brian Mulroney]] tide, electing Quebec nationalists under the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]] banner.  The [[Conservative Party of Canada]] has never approached this level of support, and eastern Montreal is currently the weakest region in Canada for the Tories. In 2011, the federalist [[New Democratic Party of Canada|NDP]] swept every seat in this region amid the surge of popular support in the province and the concurrent Bloc meltdown, in all but one case by well over 6,000 votes.  The NDP surge even cost longtime Bloc leader [[Gilles Duceppe]] his seat in [[Laurier-Sainte-Marie]].\n\nThe NDP largely held its gains in 2015, losing Honor\u00e9-Mercier to the Liberals and [[La Pointe-de-l'\u00cele]]\u2014long reckoned as the most strongly sovereigntist riding in Quebec\u2014to the Bloc.  However, Duceppe came up well short in his bid to retake his old riding. In 2019, however, the NDP was cut down to just one riding in eastern Montreal, with the Bloc holding onto La Pointe-de-l'\u00cele and the Liberals taking the other three.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"10\"|2004 ELECTION RESULTS CITY OF MONTREAL\n|-\n!align=\"centre\" colspan=2 rowspan=2|Party\n!align=\"centre\" colspan=2|[[Canadian federal election results in Western Montreal|Western]]\n!align=\"centre\" colspan=2|Eastern\n!align=\"centre\" colspan=2|[[Canadian federal election results in Northern Montreal and Laval|Northern]]\n!align=\"centre\" colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!align=\"right\"| Votes\n!align=\"right\"|%\n!align=\"right\"| Votes\n!align=\"right\"|%\n!align=\